# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deck-ship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deck-ship/1mc] During an incident involving a casualty, the 1MC is a communication tool used by DCAs (damage control assistants) to keep ship members alerted and informed of casualty location area, status, and incident response efforts by the DC organization.
[src:deck-ship/1mc] The 1MC is divided into smaller sub-circuits, such as officer's quarters and topside.
[src:deck-ship/1mc] At the option of the officer of the deck, some details are not passed on certain circuits.
[src:deck-ship/1mc] The 1MC is also used for transmitting various alarm sounds to alert the crew of specific impending dangers such as an inbound anti-ship missile, chemical attack, collision, or a flight deck crash.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] This **glossary of nautical terms** is an alphabetical listing of terms and expressions connected with ships, shipping, seamanship and navigation on water (mostly though not necessarily on the sea).
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] Some remain current, while many date from the 17th to 19th centuries.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] The word **nautical** derives from the Latin *nauticus*, from Greek *nautikos*, from *nautēs*: "sailor", from *naus*: "ship".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] Further information on nautical terminology may also be found at Nautical metaphors in English, and additional military terms are listed in the Multiservice tactical brevity code article.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] Terms used in other fields associated with bodies of water can be found at Glossary of fishery terms, Glossary of underwater diving terminology, Glossary of rowing terms, and Glossary of meteorology.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] ) Filled by the wind on the opposite side to the one normally used to move the vessel forward.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] A sudden shift in the wind can also cause a square-rigged vessel to be unintentionally "caught aback" with all sails aback.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] This is a dangerous situation that risks serious damage.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] or by tacking without releasing the sheet.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] It is used to heave to or to assist with tacking.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] "two points abaft the beam, starboard side" would describe "an object lying 22.5 degrees toward the rear of the ship, as measured clockwise from a perpendicular line from the right side, center, of the ship, toward the horizon".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p01] An imperative to leave the vessel immediately, usually in the face of some imminent overwhelming danger.
