[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A spar to extend the foot of gaffsail, trysail or jib.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Booms'l rig could also refer to cutter-rigged early barges.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A sail control that lets one apply downward tension on a boom, countering the upward tension provided by the sail.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] The boom vang adds an element of control to sail shape when the sheet is let out enough that it no longer pulls the boom down.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Boom vang tension helps control leech twist, a primary component of sail power.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Masts or yards, lying on board in reserve.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] ) To assume a position to engage, or disengage, the enemy ships.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A device for adjusting tension in stays, shrouds and similar lines.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] The underside of a vessel; the portion of a vessel that is always underwater.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Pledging a ship as security in a financial transaction.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Something ahead and to the left of the vessel is "off the port bow", while something ahead and to the right of the vessel is "off the starboard bow".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A type of knot producing a strong loop of a fixed size, topologically similar to a sheet bend.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] (for keeping the windward edge of the sail steady).
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] "Sailing on a bowline" means sailing to weather close-hauled.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Seas approaching a vessel from between 15° and 75° to port or starboard.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] On a barge it may be pivoted so it may be steeved up in harbor.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A small propeller or water-jet at the bow, used for manoeuvring larger vessels at slow speed.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] May be mounted externally, or in a tunnel running through the bow from side to side.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A feature of some ships, particularly ferries and roll-on/roll-off ships, that allows a vessel's bow to articulate up and down to provide access to her cargo ramp and storage deck near the waterline.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] The wave created on either side of a vessel's bow as she moves through the water.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A structure fitted on the bow of some containerships to decrease aerodynamic drag and improve fuel efficiency.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] To state all 32 points of the compass, starting at north and proceeding clockwise.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Sometimes applied to a wind that is constantly shifting.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Braces are fitted in pairs to each yard, one at each end.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] To furl a sail by pulling it in towards the mast and/or to the yard or gaff on which it is set .
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Where the brailing action is mostly moving towards the mast, it is termed "brailing in".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] If the sail is generally moving up to a spar, that is called "brailing up".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A line used to haul the edges or corners of a sail up or in, either preparatory to furling or as the act of furling the sail.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Some brails do not have a more specific name, especially on a fore and aft sail.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] and leechlines may be considered types of brails.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A device consisting of a net of small-mesh webbing attached to a frame, used aboard fishing vessels for unloading large quantities of fish.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] The handle of the pump, by which it is worked.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Used in the expression "it is cold enough to freeze the balls off a brass monkey".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Apocryphally, it is often claimed that a brass monkey was a frame used to hold cannon balls, and low temperature would cause the frame to contract to a greater degree than the iron balls and thus allow them to roll off.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] The whole area around the place where a channel meets the ocean.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Goods that must be loaded aboard a ship individually and not in intermodal containers or in bulk, carried by a general cargo ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A shallow portion of a reef over which waves break.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] that breaks into foam against the shore, a shoal, a rock or a reef.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Sailors use breakers to warn themselves of their vessel's proximity to an underwater hazard to navigation or, at night or during periods of poor visibility, of their vessel's proximity to shore.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] in case of becoming separated from the ship or if used as a lifeboat.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] of a ship intended to divert water away from the forward superstructure or gun mounts.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] , used to transfer people from one ship to another or to rescue people from a wrecked or sinking ship by moving them to another ship or to the shore.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A mooring rope fastened anywhere on a ship's side that goes directly to the quay, so that it is roughly at right angles to both.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] personnel a full view to aid in the maneuvering of the ship, such as when docking.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] , and to punish delinquent crew members.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Usually resembles a prison cell with bars and a locked, hinged door.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Exposed varnished wood on a boat or ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] To cause a ship to be stationary by arranging the sails.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] When a sailing or power vessel loses directional control when travelling with a following sea.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Advice on dealing with heavy weather includes various strategies for avoiding this happening.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] , a dangerous event when the submarine is in proximity to enemy forces or near any ship which might collide with her.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] with her side facing the viewer's ship could be described as "broad on the starboard bow" of the viewer's ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] On a nautical chart with depths indicated in fathoms, it appears as a broad area with many "14" notations.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] ) so as to be able to fire on the same side of a warship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] The simultaneous firing of all the guns on one side of a warship or able to fire on the same side of a warship.
