[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] at the time, ships which missed the northward turn ran the risk of being wrecked on the west coast of Australia.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A collective term for rivers and coastal waters.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A navy capable of operating on rivers and/or in coastal environments.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] That portion of a navy designed and intended to operate on rivers and/or in coastal environments.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A navy whose capabilities limit it to operating on rivers and/or in coastal environments.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Alternative name for a paddle on a paddlewheel.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] 's mate (in the Royal Navy), responsible for discipline.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] which modifies the way water flows around the hull, reducing drag and thus increasing speed, range, fuel efficiency and stability.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Commodity cargo that is transported unpackaged in large quantities.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] of a ship, particularly a watertight, load-bearing wall.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] The senior ensign of a US Navy command (i.e., a ship, squadron or shore activity).
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A glass window above the captain's cabin to allow viewing of the sails above deck.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A container for storing coal or fuel oil for a ship's engine.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] Canvas apron used to fasten the bunt of a square sail to the yard when furled.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] A signalman who prepares and flies flag hoists.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p02] One of the lines leading from the foot of a square sail over a block at the head and down to the deck; and used to haul it up to the yard when furling.
