[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] between the 18th century and around the third quarter of the 19th century.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The senior engineering officer (abbreviated ChEng).
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A line formed where the sides of a boat meet the bottom.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Soft chine is when the two sides join at a shallow angle, and hard chine is when they join at a steep angle.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] that are so tight against one another that they cannot be further tightened.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The invention of the marine chronometer in the 18th century was a major technical achievement for maritime navigation.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Previously, a fortified room to protect ammunition and machinery from damage.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Strictly, a group of government ships, especially naval ships, of the same or similar design.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Informally, a group of private or commercial ships of the same or similar design.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A certificate issued by a port indicating that a ship carries no infectious diseases.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] would record details of speed, distances, headings, etc. on a slate.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] At the beginning of a new watch the slate would be wiped clean.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A stationary device used to secure a rope aboard a vessel.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A method of fixing together two pieces of wood, usually overlapping planks, by driving a nail through both planks as well as a washer-like rove.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The nail is then burred or riveted over to complete the fastening.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] that involves overlapping planks and/or plates, much like Viking longships, resulting in speed and flexibility in small boat hulls.
