[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A time-consuming, laborious, and dirty process often undertaken by the entire crew, coaling was a necessity from the early days of steam in the 19th century until the early 20th century, when oil supplanted coal as the fuel of choice for steamships.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The raised edge of a hatch, cockpit, or skylight, designed to help keep out water that pools on the surface above.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] ; a shallow-hulled ship used for trade between locations on the same island or continent.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A type of open traditional fishing boat with a flat bottom and high bow which developed on the northeast coast of England.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] away from the horizontal so that it is out of the way for loading or unloading, or so that the ship may lie alongside another ship without the yards touching.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] An insulating space between two watertight bulkheads or decks within a ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] region, in seagoing trade from the 12th through the 14th centuries.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A wedge used to assist in the aiming of a cannon; an older form of "quoin".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] designed to carry coal, especially such a ship in naval use to supply coal to coal-fired warships.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A way of loading a vessel that gives military forces embarked aboard her immediate access to weapons, ammunition, and supplies needed when conducting an amphibious landing.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] In combat loading, cargo is stowed in such a way that unloading of equipment will match up with the personnel that are landing and in the order they land, so that they have immediate access to the gear they need for combat as soon as they land.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Combat loading gives primary consideration to the ease and sequence with which troops, equipment, and supplies can be made ready for combat, sacrificing the more efficient use of cargo space that ship operators seek when loading a ship for the routine transportation of personnel and cargo.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A long, curving wave breaking on the shore.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] of a sailing vessel across the wind so that the wind changes from one side of the vessel to the other.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] To position a vessel with respect to the wind after tacking.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] To stop a sailing vessel, especially by turning into the wind.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Also called "CO", "captain" (regardless of rank), "skipper", or "the old man".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Sometimes used less formally to mean placing a commercial ship into service.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Often equivalent to the rank of "flotilla admiral" or sometimes "counter admiral" in non-English-speaking navies.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] , but with no authority over naval ships escorting the convoy.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] and the below-decks control spaces on a warship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A collective term for all of the persons in a ship's crew, including officers.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] As applied to a naval task force, the listing of all assigned units for a single transient purpose or mission (e.g.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] "Comprise" means exhaustive inclusion – there are not any other parts to the task force, and each ship has a permanent squadron existence, independent of the task force.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] ) rather than of more traditional materials, such as steel, iron, or wood.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Waters where there is little space to maneuver.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] To direct a ship or submarine from a position of command.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] An armored control tower of an iron or steel warship built between the mid-19th and mid-20th centuries from which the ship was navigated in battle.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] (European and Commonwealth usage), a structure similar in appearance that no longer plays a role in directing the submarine.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] barge, towed by a larger steamer that would often tow more than one barge.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The consort system was used in the Great Lakes from the 1860s to around 1920.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Because of the implication of collision, "constant bearing, decreasing range" has come to mean a problem or an obstacle which is incoming.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A group of ships traveling together for mutual support and protection.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A device used to correct the ship's compass, e.g. by counteracting errors due to the magnetic effects of a steel hull.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A ship used by privateers or pirates, especially of French nationality.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A lightly armed and armored warship of the 20th and 21st centuries, smaller than a frigate and capable of transoceanic duty.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] To deliberately flood compartments on the opposite side from already flooded ones.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] "Country ships" were strictly prohibited from trading west of the Cape, which would violate the company's strict monopoly on that trade.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Country ships were also important in the opium trade from India into China until supplanted by the faster opium clipper.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The direction in which a vessel is being steered, usually given in degrees.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A ship's ventilator with a bell-shaped top that can be swiveled to catch the wind and force it below.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] is off-limits to more junior enlisted personnel unless they are there on official business.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A ship with a crane and specialized for lifting heavy loads.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A term used in the United States to describe military high-speed offshore rescue boats, similar in size and performance to motor torpedo boats, used to rescue pilots and aircrews of crashed aircraft.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] US Navy slang for a maneuver in which a submerged Soviet or Russian submarine suddenly turns 180 degrees or through 360 degrees to detect submarines following it.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] On leisure vessels with no formal chain of command, all of those persons who are not the skipper or passengers.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A vessel specialized for the transportation of offshore support personnel and cargo to and from offshore installations such as oil platforms, drilling rigs, drill ships, dive ships, and wind farms.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] They are often reinforced with a metal eye.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Lateral spreaders for the topmast shrouds (standing back stays).
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] constructed with sides and sometimes a roof to shelter the lookouts from the weather, generally by whaling vessels.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The term has also become generic for what is properly called a masthead.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A passenger ship used for pleasure voyages, where the voyage itself and the ship's amenities are the purpose of the experience, as are the different destinations along the way.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Transportation is not the prime purpose, as cruise ships operate mostly on routes that return passengers to their originating port.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] , which is a passenger ship that provides a scheduled service between published ports primarily as a mode of transportation.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] , capable of both direct support of a battle fleet and of independent operations, armed with guns and sometimes torpedoes.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] and associated task forces or for anti-ship missile attacks against such forces; virtually indistinguishable from large destroyers since the late 20th century.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Metal Y-shaped pins used to fix oars while rowing.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A join between two lines, similar to an eye-splice, where each rope end is joined to the other a short distance along, making an opening that closes under tension.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The "valley" between the strands of a rope or cable.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] , it may be "wormed" by laying yarns in the cuntlines, giving that section an even cylindrical shape.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] The "cut" of a sail refers to its shape.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] Since this would often vary between ships, it could be used both to identify a familiar vessel at a distance, and to judge the possible sailing qualities of an unknown one.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] that could be determined at a distance, providing an easy way to determine friend from foe.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] In North American waters, the definition also considers whether or not the bowsprit is permanently fixed and also takes into account the position of the mast.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A standing (permanently fixed) bowsprit and a forward mast position, but with two or more headsails would be classed as a sloop in the North American definition.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A running bowsprit, a forestay (carrying a staysail) that is fixed to the stemhead, a jib that is set flying and a mast position that is more aft is a cutter.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] powered by sail or oars, though more optimised for sail than many types of ship's boat.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A type of decked sailing vessel originating in the early 18th century designed for speed.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] ed with both fore-and-aft and square sails.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A cutter rig had very large sail areas available for use in light winds.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p03] A surprise attack by small boats, often at night, against an anchored vessel in which the small-boat crews boarded and captured or destroyed the target vessel.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] consisting of a long pole with flag and/or light at the top and, lower down, a float and a ballast weight to make it float vertically.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] May be used with or without an anchor to attach it to the sea bed.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] In naval use often marks a swept channel created by minesweeping.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] In British usage, a small after-sail on a yawl.
