[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] A strong shutter fitted over a porthole or other opening that can be closed in bad weather.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] A method of navigation that estimates a ship's position from the distance run measured by the log and the course steered.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] If corrections for factors such as tide and leeway are then made, this provides an estimated position.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] Some sources consider that a dead reckoning position does include adjustments for wind and tide, so care is needed in interpretation of this term.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] Without any other qualifier, it is taken at the midships cross-section of the hull.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] This can be expressed in degrees or sometimes as a vertical linear measure (such as inches) at a standard distance from the keel.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] A hull with a lot of deadrise has an obvious "V" shape to the bottom of the hull, whereas no deadrise denotes sheer sides and a flat-bottomed hull.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] It is usually taken to be one of several measures of the "sharpness" of a hull.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] In a traditional wooden hull, blocks of timber on the top of the keel that form the shape of the hull where its section is too narrow for the method of construction employed elsewhere.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] , which sweep across the deck and plunge down into the water.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] or the skipper reacts correctly to prevent it.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] The process of leaving a ship or aircraft, or removing goods from a ship or aircraft.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] The process of removing fuel from a vessel.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] After a shipwreck, a "debunkering" operation will be performed in an effort to minimize damage and protect the environment from fuel spills.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] The top of a ship or vessel; the surface that is removed to accommodate the seating area.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] Any of the structures forming the approximately horizontal surfaces in the ship's general structure.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] Unlike flats, they are a structural part of the ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] A person whose job involves aiding the deck supervisor in (un)mooring, anchoring, maintenance, and general evolutions on deck.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] The person in charge of all evolutions and maintenance on deck; sometimes split into two groups: forward deck supervisor and aft deck supervisor.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] The inside of the boat is normally paneled over to hide the structure, pipes, electrical wires.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] It can be in thin wood planks, often covered with a vinyl lining, or in thin PVC or now even in fiberglass planks.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] Sometimes used less formally to mean taking a commercial ship out of service.
