[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] Especially in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, a permanent battle formation of a fleet, often smaller than a squadron, equipped and trained to operate as a tactical unit under the overall command of a higher command, such as a fleet or squadron.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] Especially in modern usage, an administrative naval command, smaller than a squadron and often subordinate to an administrative squadron, responsible for the manning, training, supply, and maintenance of a group of ships or submarines but not for directing their operations at sea.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] refers more generally to facilities used for tying up ships or boats, including recreational craft.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] In British usage, the body of water between two piers or wharves that accommodates vessels tied up at the piers or wharves.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p04] A facility where ships or boats are built and repaired.
