[src:deck-ship/abaft-p06] Both vessel speed and wind speed are commonly reported in knots.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p06] can identify all the many ropes used in working a sailing vessel.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p06] On a square rigged ship, there would typically be more than 130 named ropes in the running rigging which are made fast at deck level – the majority of these are duplicated on both the port and starboard sides, so doubling that count.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p06] at deck level on a square-rigged ship, so a newly signed-on hand would quickly know where to find a particular rope on a strange ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] On board a ship, all "stairs" are called ladders, except for literal staircases aboard passenger ships.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] Most "stairs" on a ship are extremely narrow and nearly vertical, hence the name.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] The latter usage in modern times refers to a specific set of procedures used by the United States Navy to preserve ships in good condition.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] slang for a vessel that spends all of her time on any of the five Great Lakes.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] term for the general cargo and passenger trade between settlements on the Great Lakes during the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] A person unfamiliar with being on the sea or with the workings of a seafaring vessel.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] In now-obsolete usage, the first land discovered after a sea voyage.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] An object ashore that is visible from sea and sufficiently distinct such that it is marked on nautical charts for the purpose of fixing position while at sea.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] A military rank for a naval recruit, used in the United Kingdom in the 18th century and the first half of the 19th century and in the United States in the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] Solid shot suitable for damaging rigging.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] Rope in which the lay of the strands is on the same hand as the lay of the constituents of the strands.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] that suspends a small item to prevent loss or is used to operate something by pulling on it.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] An obsolete term for the left side of a ship.
