[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] Literally, having cargo loaded as high as the ship's rail.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] The term is also used as an idiom meaning "extremely drunk".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] In boat construction, a drafting technique used to convert a scaled drawing to full size.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] for snubbing the whale line as a harpooned whale swam away from the boat.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] An iron ball attached to a long handle, used for driving caulking into seams and (occasionally) in a fight; hence the expression "at loggerheads".
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] to either side caused by inadequate transverse stability in the upright condition.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] On nautical charts with depths indicated in fathoms, it appears as a long area with many "40" notations.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] The largest, and thus the most capable, of boats carried on a ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] , referring to the slender appearance of such vessels.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] A type of ship invented and used by the Vikings for trade, commerce, exploration, and warfare, evolving over several centuries and appearing in its complete form between the 9th and 13th centuries.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] specifically assigned to watch surrounding waters for other vessels, land, objects in the water, hazards, threats, etc.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] , in order to enhance their field of view.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] An irresponsible and reckless individual whose behavior (either intentionally or unintentionally) endangers the group he or she belongs to.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] The term refers to a hypothetical literal loose cannon which, weighing thousands of pounds, would crush anything and anyone in its path, and possibly even break a hole in the hull, thus endangering the seaworthiness of the whole ship.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] The design combines the ease of handling of a junk rig with the greater speed, cargo capacity, and ease of repair of the European-style hull.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] who are not officers, often used in the plural (e.g., "the lower decks").
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] , and few sailors would risk the scorn of their shipmates by doing so (at least if there were witnesses).
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] In practice, it is often actually quicker and easier for a fit sailor to climb outside the masthead than through the lubber's hole.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] A line or mark inside or on a compass case or binnacle indicating the direction of the ship's head.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] A locker or compartment for storage of unclaimed articles.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] To point a sailing vessel closer to the wind.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] To bring a vessel so close to the wind that the sails shake.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] , which is a perpendicular line from the luff to the clew.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] Commonly given as a percentage of the "J" measurement.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] so far past optimal trim that the sail no longer completely fills with wind.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] The flapping of a sail from having no wind at all.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] and running gear to carry large cargoes of lumber.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] , widely used as traditional fishing boats, particularly off the coasts of France, England, and Scotland; also used as privateers and smugglers.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] at a point some distance from the center of the spar.
[src:deck-ship/abaft-p07] A standing lug can be used on either tack in the same position.
[src:deck-ship/aft] This **list of ship directions** provides succinct definitions for terms applying to spatial orientation in a marine environment or location on a vessel, such as *fore*, *aft*, *astern*, *aboard*, or *topside*.
[src:deck-ship/aftercastle] The **aftercastle** (or **sterncastle**, sometimes **aftcastle**) is the stern structure behind the mizzenmast and above the transom on large sailing ships, such as carracks, caravels, galleons and galleasses.
[src:deck-ship/aftercastle] It usually houses the captain's cabin and perhaps additional cabins and is crowned by the poop deck, which on men-of-war provided a heightened platform from which to fire upon other ships; it was also a place of defence in the event of boarding.
[src:deck-ship/aftercastle] More common, but much smaller, is the forecastle.
[src:deck-ship/aftercastle] The corresponding term *forecastle* today is also used to describe the upper deck of a sailing ship forward of the foremast in general.
[src:deck-ship/aftercastle] As sailing ships evolved, the aftercastle gave way to the quarterdeck, whose span ran all the way to the main mast.
[src:deck-ship/afterdeck] In naval architecture, an **afterdeck** or **after deck**, or sometimes the **aftdeck**, **aft deck** or **a-deck** is the open deck area toward the stern or aft back part of a ship or boat.
[src:deck-ship/afterdeck] The afterdeck can be used for a number of different purposes, yet not all ships have an afterdeck.
[src:deck-ship/afterdeck] In place of the afterdeck, a ship may be built with a poop deck, that is a deck that forms the roof of a cabin built in the rear, or "aft", part of the superstructure of a ship; a poop deck is usually higher up than an afterdeck.
[src:deck-ship/afterdeck] A ship may have its superstructure or aftercastle located in the stern and thus not have an afterdeck.
[src:deck-ship/afterdeck] The stern and afterdeck of a ship are usually more smooth and stable than the bow (front) of the ship in motion.
[src:deck-ship/afterdeck] A taffrail is the handrail around the open afterdeck or poop deck.
[src:deck-ship/afterdeck] On wooden sailing ships like man-of-war or East Indiaman the taffrail is usually a hand carved wood rail and often highly decorated.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:deck-ship/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] An **anchor** is a device, normally made of metal, used to secure a vessel to the bed of a body of water to prevent the craft from drifting due to wind or current.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The word derives from Latin **ancora**, which itself comes from the Greek ἄγκυρα (*ankȳra*).
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Anchors can either be temporary or permanent.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Permanent anchors are used in the creation of a mooring, and are rarely moved; a specialist service is normally needed to move or maintain them.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Vessels carry one or more temporary anchors, which may be of different designs and weights.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A sea anchor is a drag device, not in contact with the seabed, used to minimize drift of a vessel relative to the water.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A drogue is a drag device used to slow or help steer a vessel running before a storm in a following or overtaking sea, or when crossing a bar in a breaking sea.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Anchors achieve holding power either by "hooking" into the seabed, or weight, or a combination of the two.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The weight of the anchor chain can be more than that of the anchor and is critical to proper holding.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Permanent moorings use large masses (commonly a block or slab of concrete) resting on the seabed.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Semi-permanent mooring anchors (such as mushroom anchors) and large ship's anchors derive a significant portion of their holding power from their weight, while also hooking or embedding in the bottom.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Modern anchors for smaller vessels have metal *flukes* that hook on to rocks on the bottom or bury themselves in soft seabed.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The vessel is attached to the anchor by the *rode* (also called a *cable* or a *warp*).
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It can be made of rope, chain or a combination of rope and chain.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The ratio of the length of rode to the water depth is known as the scope.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Holding ground is the area of sea floor that holds an anchor, and thus the attached ship or boat.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Different types of anchor are designed to hold in different types of holding ground.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Some bottom materials hold better than others; for instance, hard sand holds well, shell holds poorly.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Holding ground may be fouled with obstacles.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] An anchorage location may be chosen for its holding ground.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In poor holding ground, only the weight of an anchor and chain matters; in good holding ground, it is able to dig in, and the holding power can be significantly higher.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The basic anchoring consists of determining the location, dropping the anchor, laying out the scope, setting the hook, and assessing where the vessel ends up.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The ship seeks a location that is sufficiently protected; has suitable holding ground, enough depth at low tide and enough room for the boat to swing.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The location to drop the anchor should be approached from down wind or down current, whichever is stronger.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] As the chosen spot is approached, the vessel should be stopped or even beginning to drift back.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The anchor should initially be lowered quickly but under control until it is on the bottom (see anchor windlass).
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The vessel should continue to drift back, and the cable should be veered out under control (slowly) so it is relatively straight.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Once the desired scope is laid out, the vessel should be gently forced astern, usually using the auxiliary motor but possibly by backing a sail.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A hand on the anchor line may telegraph a series of jerks and jolts, indicating the anchor is dragging, or a smooth tension indicative of digging in.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] As the anchor begins to dig in and resist backward force, the engine may be throttled up to get a thorough set.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Lowering a concentrated, heavy weight down the anchor line – rope or chain – directly in front of the bow to the seabed behaves like a heavy chain rode and lowers the angle of pull on the anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] If the weight is suspended off the seabed it acts as a spring or shock absorber to dampen the sudden actions that are normally transmitted to the anchor and can cause it to dislodge and drag.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In light conditions, a kellet reduces the swing of the vessel considerably.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In heavier conditions these effects disappear as the rode becomes straightened and the weight ineffective.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Known as an "anchor chum weight" or "angel" in the UK.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Using two anchors set approximately 45° apart, or wider angles up to 90°, from the bow is a strong mooring for facing into strong winds.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] To set anchors in this way, first one anchor is set in the normal fashion.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Then, taking in on the first cable as the boat is motored into the wind and letting slack while drifting back, a second anchor is set approximately a half-scope away from the first on a line perpendicular to the wind.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] After this second anchor is set, the scope on the first is taken up until the vessel is lying between the two anchors and the load is taken equally on each cable.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This moor also to some degree limits the range of a vessel's swing to a narrower oval.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Care should be taken that other vessels do not swing down on the boat due to the limited swing range.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] (Not to be mistaken with the *Bahamian moor*, below.) In the *bow and stern* technique, an anchor is set off each the bow and the stern, which can severely limit a vessel's swing range and also align it to steady wind, current or wave conditions.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] One method of accomplishing this moor is to set a bow anchor normally, then drop back to the limit of the bow cable (or to double the desired scope, e.g.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] 8:1 if the eventual scope should be 4:1, 10:1 if the eventual scope should be 5:1, etc.) to lower a stern anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] By taking up on the bow cable the stern anchor can be set.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] After both anchors are set, tension is taken up on both cables to limit the swing or to align the vessel.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Similar to the above, a *Bahamian moor* is used to sharply limit the swing range of a vessel, but allows it to swing to a current.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] One of the primary characteristics of this technique is the use of a swivel as follows: the first anchor is set normally, and the vessel drops back to the limit of anchor cable.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A second anchor is attached to the end of the anchor cable, and is dropped and set.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A swivel is attached to the middle of the anchor cable, and the vessel connected to that.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The vessel now swings in the middle of two anchors, which is acceptable in strong reversing currents, but a wind perpendicular to the current may break out the anchors, as they are not aligned for this load.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Also known as *tandem anchoring*, in this technique two anchors are deployed in line with each other, on the same rode.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] With the foremost anchor reducing the load on the aft-most, this technique can develop great holding power and may be appropriate in "ultimate storm" circumstances.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It does not limit swinging range, and might not be suitable in some circumstances.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] There are complications, and the technique requires careful preparation and a level of skill and experience above that required for a single anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In yachts, a kedge anchor is an anchor carried in addition to the main, or bower, anchor, and usually stowed aft.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Every yacht should carry at least two anchors – the main or *bower* anchor and a second lighter *kedge* anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It is used occasionally when it is necessary to limit the turning circle as the yacht swings when it is anchored, such as in a narrow river or a deep pool in an otherwise shallow area.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Kedge anchors are sometimes used to recover vessels that have run aground.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] For ships, a kedge may be dropped while a ship is underway, or carried out in a suitable direction by a tender or ship's boat to enable the ship to be winched off if aground or swung into a particular heading, or even to be held steady against a tidal or other stream.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Historically, it was of particular relevance to sailing warships that used them to outmaneuver opponents when the wind had dropped but might be used by any vessel in confined, shoal water to place it in a more desirable position, provided she had enough manpower.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] When a vessel is in a narrow channel or on a lee shore so that there is no room to tack the vessel in a conventional manner, an anchor attached to the lee quarter may be dropped from the lee bow.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This is deployed when the vessel is head to wind and has lost headway.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] As the vessel gathers sternway the strain on the cable pivots the vessel around what is now the weather quarter turning the vessel onto the other tack.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The anchor is then normally cut away (the ship's momentum prevents recovery without aborting the maneuver).
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The anchors are usually laid in prearranged positions by an anchor tender, and the moored vessel uses its own winches to adjust position and tension.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Similar arrangements are used for some types of single buoy moorings, like the catenary anchor leg mooring (CALM) used for loading and unloading liquid cargoes.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Since all anchors that embed themselves in the bottom require the strain to be along the seabed, anchors can be broken out of the bottom by shortening the rope until the vessel is directly above the anchor; at this point the anchor chain is "up and down", in naval parlance.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] If necessary, motoring slowly around the location of the anchor also helps dislodge it.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Anchors are sometimes fitted with a trip line attached to the crown, by which they can be unhooked from underwater hazards.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The term *aweigh* describes an anchor when it is hanging on the rope and not resting on the bottom.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This is linked to the term *to weigh anchor*, meaning to lift the anchor from the sea bed, allowing the ship or boat to move.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] An anchor is described as *aweigh* when it has been broken out of the bottom and is being hauled up to be *stowed*.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] *Aweigh* should not be confused with *under way*, which describes a vessel that is not *moored* to a dock or *anchored*, whether or not the vessel is moving through the water.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] *Aweigh* is also often confused with *away*, which is incorrect.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The earliest anchors were probably rocks, and many rock anchors have been found dating from at least the Bronze Age.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Pre-European Māori waka (canoes) used one or more hollowed stones, tied with flax ropes, as anchors.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Many modern moorings still rely on a large rock as the primary element of their design.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] However, using pure weight to resist the forces of a storm works well only as a permanent mooring; a large enough rock would be nearly impossible to move to a new location.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The ancient Greeks used baskets of stones, large sacks filled with sand, and wooden logs filled with lead as a weight for their ships.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Influential authors such as Apollonius Rhodius and Stephen of Byzantium also show that they may be made out of wood, Athenaeus also referring to anchors made out of metals.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Such anchors held the vessel merely by their weight and by their friction along the bottom.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Iron was afterwards introduced for the construction of anchors, and an improvement was made by forming them with teeth, or "flukes", to fasten themselves into the bottom.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This is the iconic anchor shape most familiar to non-sailors.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This form has been used since antiquity.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The Roman Nemi ships of the 1st century AD used this form.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The Viking Ladby ship (probably 10th century) used a fluked anchor of this type, made of iron, which would have had a wooden stock mounted perpendicular to the shank and flukes to make the flukes contact the bottom at a suitable angle to hook or penetrate.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The Admiralty Pattern anchor, or simply "Admiralty", also known as a "Fisherman", consists of a central shank with a ring or shackle for attaching the rode (the rope, chain, or cable connecting the ship and the anchor).
[src:deck-ship/anchor] At the other end of the shank there are two arms, carrying the flukes, while the stock is mounted to the shackle end, at ninety degrees to the arms.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] When the anchor lands on the bottom, it generally falls over with the arms parallel to the seabed.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] As a strain comes onto the rope, the stock digs into the bottom, canting the anchor until one of the flukes catches and digs into the bottom.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The Admiralty Anchor is an entirely independent reinvention of a classical design, as seen in one of the Nemi ship anchors.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This basic design remained unchanged for centuries, with the most significant changes being to the overall proportions, and a move from stocks made of wood to iron stocks in the late 1830s and early 1840s.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Since one fluke always protrudes up from the set anchor, there is a great tendency of the rode to foul the anchor as the vessel swings due to wind or current shifts.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] When this happens, the anchor may be pulled out of the bottom, and in some cases may need to be hauled up to be re-set.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In the mid-19th century, numerous modifications were attempted to alleviate these problems, as well as improve holding power, including one-armed mooring anchors.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The most successful of these *patent anchors*, the Trotman Anchor, introduced a pivot at the centre of the crown where the arms join the shank, allowing the "idle" upper arm to fold against the shank.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] When deployed the lower arm may fold against the shank tilting the tip of the fluke upwards, so each fluke has a tripping palm at its base, to hook on the bottom as the folded arm drags along the seabed, which unfolds the downward oriented arm until the tip of the fluke can engage the bottom.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Handling and storage of these anchors requires special equipment and procedures.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Once the anchor is hauled up to the hawsepipe, the ring end is hoisted up to the end of a timber projecting from the bow known as the cathead.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The crown of the anchor is then hauled up with a heavy tackle until one fluke can be hooked over the rail.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This is known as "catting and fishing" the anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Before dropping the anchor, the fishing process is reversed, and the anchor is dropped from the end of the cathead.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The stockless anchor, patented in England in 1821, represented the first significant departure in anchor design in centuries.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Although their holding-power-to-weight ratio is significantly lower than admiralty pattern anchors, their ease of handling and stowage aboard large ships led to almost universal adoption.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In contrast to the elaborate stowage procedures for earlier anchors, stockless anchors are simply hauled up until they rest with the shank inside the hawsepipes, and the flukes against the hull (or inside a recess in the hull called the anchor box).
[src:deck-ship/anchor] While there are numerous variations, stockless anchors consist of a set of heavy flukes connected by a pivot or ball and socket joint to a shank.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Cast into the crown of the anchor is a set of tripping palms, projections that drag on the bottom, forcing the main flukes to dig in.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Until the mid-20th century, anchors for smaller vessels were either scaled-down versions of admiralty anchors, or simple grapnels.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] As new designs with greater holding-power-to-weight ratios were sought, a great variety of anchor designs have emerged.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Many of these designs are still under patent, and other types are best known by their original trademarked names.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A traditional design, the grapnel is merely a shank (no stock) with four or more tines, also known as a *drag*.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It has a benefit in that, no matter how it reaches the bottom, one or more tines are aimed to set.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In coral, or rock, it is often able to set quickly by hooking into the structure, but may be more difficult to retrieve.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A grapnel is often quite light, and may have additional uses as a tool to recover gear lost overboard.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Its weight also makes it relatively easy to move and carry, however its shape is generally not compact and it may be awkward to stow unless a collapsing model is used.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Grapnels rarely have enough fluke area to develop much hold in sand, clay, or mud.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It is not unknown for the anchor to foul on its own rode, or to foul the tines with refuse from the bottom, preventing it from digging in.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] On the other hand, it is quite possible for this anchor to find such a good hook that, without a trip line from the crown, it is impossible to retrieve.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Francis Herreshoff, this is essentially the same pattern as an admiralty anchor, albeit with small diamond-shaped flukes or palms.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The novelty of the design lay in the means by which it could be broken down into three pieces for stowage.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In use, it still presents all the issues of the admiralty pattern anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Originally designed as a lightweight anchor for seaplanes, this design consists of two plough-like blades mounted to a shank, with a folding stock crossing through the crown of the anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Many manufacturers produce a plough-type anchor, so-named after its resemblance to an agricultural plough.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] All such anchors are copied from the original CQR (*Coastal Quick Release*, or *Clyde Quick Release*, later rebranded as 'secure' by Lewmar), a 1933 design patented in the UK by mathematician Geoffrey Ingram Taylor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Plough anchors stow conveniently in a roller at the bow, and have been popular with cruising sailors and private boaters.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Ploughs can be moderately good in all types of seafloor, though not exceptional in any.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Contrary to popular belief, the CQR's hinged shank is not to allow the anchor to turn with direction changes rather than breaking out, but actually to prevent the shank's weight from disrupting the fluke's orientation while setting.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The hinge can wear out and may trap a sailor's fingers.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Some later plough anchors have a rigid shank, such as the Lewmar's "Delta".
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A plough anchor has a fundamental flaw: like its namesake, the agricultural plough, it digs in but then tends to break out back to the surface.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Plough anchors sometimes have difficulty setting at all, and instead skip across the seafloor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] By contrast, modern efficient anchors tend to be "scoop" types that dig ever deeper.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The Delta anchor was derived from the CQR.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It was patented by Philip McCarron, James Stewart, and Gordon Lyall of British marine manufacturer Simpson-Lawrence Ltd in 1992.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It was designed as an advance over the anchors used for floating systems such as oil rigs.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It retains the weighted tip of the CQR but has a much higher fluke area to weight ratio than its predecessor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The designers also eliminated the sometimes troublesome hinge.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It is a plough anchor with a rigid, arched shank.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It is described as *self-launching* because it can be dropped from a bow roller simply by paying out the rode, without manual assistance.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This is an oft copied design with the European Brake and Australian Sarca Excel being two of the more notable ones.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Although it is a plough type anchor, it sets and holds reasonably well in hard bottoms.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] American Richard Danforth invented the Danforth Anchor in the 1940s for use aboard landing craft.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It uses a stock at the crown to which two large flat triangular flukes are attached.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The stock is hinged so the flukes can orient toward the bottom (and on some designs may be adjusted for an optimal angle depending on the bottom type).
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Tripping palms at the crown act to tip the flukes into the seabed.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The design is a burying variety, and once well set can develop high resistance.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Its lightweight and compact flat design make it easy to retrieve and relatively easy to store; some anchor rollers and hawsepipes can accommodate a fluke-style anchor.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] A Danforth does not usually penetrate or hold in gravel or weeds.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] In boulders and coral it may hold by acting as a hook.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] If there is much current, or if the vessel is moving while dropping the anchor, it may "kite" or "skate" over the bottom due to the large fluke area acting as a sail or wing.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The FOB HP anchor designed in Brittany in the 1970s is a Danforth variant designed to give increased holding through its use of rounded flukes setting at a 30° angle.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The Fortress is an American aluminum alloy Danforth variant that can be disassembled for storage and it features an adjustable 32° and 45° shank/fluke angle to improve holding capability in common sea bottoms such as hard sand and soft mud.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This anchor performed well in a 1989 US Naval Sea Systems Command (NAVSEA) test and in an August 2014 holding power test that was conducted in the soft mud bottoms of the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] This claw-shaped anchor was designed by Peter Bruce from Scotland in the 1970s.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Bruce gained his early reputation from the production of large-scale commercial anchors for ships and fixed installations such as oil rigs.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] It was later scaled down for small boats, and copies of this popular design abound.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] The Bruce and its copies, known generically as "claw type anchors", have been adopted on smaller boats (partly because they stow easily on a bow roller) but they are most effective in larger sizes.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Claw anchors are quite popular on charter fleets as they have a high chance of setting on the first try in many bottoms.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] They have the reputation of not breaking out with tide or wind changes, instead slowly turning in the bottom to align with the force.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Bruce anchors can have difficulty penetrating weedy bottoms and grass.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] They offer a fairly low holding-power-to-weight ratio and generally have to be oversized to compete with newer types.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Three time circumnavigator German Rolf Kaczirek invented the Bügel Anker in the 1980s.
[src:deck-ship/anchor] Kaczirek wanted an anchor that was self-righting without necessitating a ballasted tip.
